 Mainstreaming Nature-Based Solutions in Southeast Asia will require knowledge gaps to be addressed, greater awareness, increasing the evidence base, metrics for measuring success, support from institutions and stakeholders, and new and innovative financing. The urgency of global socio-ecological challenges, in particular the biodiversity and climate crisis, means transformational change is needed in Southeast Asia, for urban, ecological, technical, economic, and social systems, while still supporting sustainable development.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 4aSociology / urban. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Urban.2bisacsh1 aAng, Michelle Li Ern, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aAzhar, Badrul, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aHamel, Perrine, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aKanai, J Miguel, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aOoi, Juin Yan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aSagala, Saut, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertISEAS Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311074332640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789815011210423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9789815011210/original  a978-3-11-074332-6  ISEAS Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK